5312, "(fr)You know, sir, when you turned up at Rheza..that was something else. You saved a lot of lives that day, including mine. Do you make a habit of it?"

5313, "(fr)That's why we do the job, Laporte. Look, we call ourselves gods of war, but that implies responsibility as well as bloodshed. You kill to save."

5314, "(fr)Flight Lieutenant Ng'Mei off the Yangtze mentioned you, sir. Have you served together? "

5315, "(fr)My first combat posting was on the Yangtze, before the war broke out. Karen Ng'Mei was a sublieutenant there...she's been passing up promotions to stay there since. She sort of cultivates pilots. Might pick you out if you're lucky."

5316, "(fr)Sir, while we're out here, I want to discuss some scuttlebutt that's been going around the deck. I think I speak for the rest of the new transfers when I say I have some concerns."

5317, "(fr)I respect and value candor, Sublieutenant, but you are walking a very fine line here. This sortie is not a break from military protocol."

5318, "(fr)We all know that rooks don't last long on the Indus, sir. Word on the deck is that you're keeping the rooks at arm's length because you expect most of us to be dead inside the month."

5319, "(fr)You will probably all be dead within the month, no matter what I or anyone else might do for you. I won't lie to you about that. Do you want a hug?"

5320, "(fr)No, sir, I understand the statistics. I suppose it's just something we'll have to try not to think about. "

5321, "(fr)I don't need a damn thing from you, sir. But you are our leader. If you don't make an effort to help these people, you might as well just shoot them yourself."

5322, "(fr)Fuck you, Laporte, you sanctimonious piece of shit. You don't get to walk in to my squadron and mouth off to a superior officer."

5323, "(fr)'No matter what?' That sounds like a piss-poor excuse for a failed commander's guilt. Get over yourself, Simms. People are counting on you."

5324, "(fr)...you just crossed the line, pilot. You're going back to First Fleet in irons. This is a military, not a soap opera."

5325, "(fr)You know, sir, I transferred here to fly alongside the woman who saved my ass at Rheza. The one who called her people 'gods of war' and had more fighting spirit in her left nut than I found in all of First Fleet. Did I end up on the right ship?"

5326, "(fr)Captain Sorensen writes my evaluations, not wetnosed First Fleet society girls. Are you going somewhere with this?"

5327, "(fr)I outlived my whole squadron. I watched my gung-ho wingman drink himself into a sobbing ruin while I turned into a recreational killer. Believe me, Simms, I have an eye for people on the edge."

5328, "(fr) respect what I saw in your jacket. You're on very thin ice, Laporte, but I'm going to listen a little longer."

5329, "(fr)Or, I could ship you back to First Fleet to guard depots. I need a good wingman, not a prima donna spouting smug, self-satisfied psychobullshit."

5330, "(fr)I'm just trying to tell you, sir, that I think you're a gifted commander with a lot of experience. You could make these rooks into fierce, disciplined warriors. I'm eager to learn."

5331, "(fr)...was that a joke? Did you actually speak those words with a straight face? Are you aware that you're in a military unit, not some kind of summer camp?"

5332, "(fr)Sir, it's no secret this war's going against us. We're bleeding pilots faster than we can train new ones - I saw that firsthand. And the Tevs are building up their pilot corps as fast as ours is disintegrating."

5333, "(fr)Thanks for the strategic update, Laporte, that was so much better than the one I get every day from the Admiralty."

5334, "(fr)You're one of the only experienced pilots we have left, sir, and we have a few weeks of breathing room ahead of us. What can you get done in that time? You have a lot of raw material in these rooks."

5335, "(fr)You know, Laporte, I want to rip you a new one for insubordination...but with all the fighting lately I've neglected this kind of planning. I like how you think."

5336, "(fr)If I were in your shoes I'd be about ready to give up. But we just need to hold the line, sir. Get these pilots into fighting shape and give the Elders time to work on a way to win the war. Ubuntu will find a way."

5337, "(fr)Wow. That's really adorable. Not only do you think the Elders have any fucking idea how to win a war, you think we just need to do our jobs and it'll all be okay. What a piece of work."

5338, "(fr)I think we all know we're fucked. But I want to ask you, sir, in the spirit of your battle cry, or the Indus's stand at Rheza...are we really going to go out lying down? Because thats how this squadron feels."

5339, "(fr)That's your big concern? The squadron feels sad? I have a 400% casualty rate out here, Laporte, and nobody feels good about that. Do you think I hand-picked the mood?"

5340, "(fr)Your transfer request made it quite specific that you had some problems with First Fleet. Is Second Fleet living up to your expectations, Sublieutenant?"

5341, "(fr)Most Earthers are too deep in Ubuntu to get the job done right. In Two Fleet we honor the fallen by doing our jobs and earning some payback."

5342, "(fr)I concur, sir. The best way to honor the fallen is by carrying out our duties with unflagging diligence. And I do mean that earnestly, as trite as it sounds. It's not an easy task with so many gone."

5343, "(fr)No...no it's not. I'm sensing some veiled criticism here, Laporte."

5344, "(fr)The most exasperating thing about First Fleet was that damn 'strategic deterrence posture.' It just seemed to mean total paralysis."

5345, "(fr)You're going to see a lot of hostility towards Earth and Byrne because of that policy. It's as if they cut the rest of the Federation loose."

5346, "(fr)Sir, it's my understanding the Indus has lost most of its pilots in the past few weeks. How has that impacted morale?"

5347, "(fr)What the hell kind of question is that, Sublieutenant? Do you even need to ask? Couldn't you tell the moment you stepped off the shuttle?"

5348, "(fr)I have high hopes for my time in Second Fleet, sir. If all goes well I'm hoping to hit back against the Tevs. Maybe make a real difference in this war."

5349, "(fr)Don't get your hopes up, Sublieutenant, I've heard those same words from a lot of lips."

5350, "(fr)I heard that kind of fatalistic talk in First Fleet, sir, but I didn't expect it from you. Have conditions changed aboard the Indus since you intervened at Rheza?"

5351, "(fr)We've lost a lot of pilots over the last few weeks. It's not a topic appropriate for this sortie. Focus on your instruments, pilot."

5352, "(fr)I think this group of rooks is special, sir. Consider it a fresh start. If we come together as a squadron I expect we'll give the Tevs something to think about."

5353, "(fr)I have no doubt you're correct, Sublieutenant, the Tevs will certainly give our squadron some thought...of one sort or another. Piece of advice? Don't think too far ahead."

5354, "(fr)We have a good history together, Simms. We both saw the Meridian attack...it only took a few squadrons and a single frigate team to pull that off. We saved Rheza. We can do that again."

5355, "(fr)...those are some of the better memories of the past few weeks, Laporte. I appreciate that. It's easy to lose sight of those victories"

5356, "(fr)Sir, I'll be honest. I wasn't a good fit for First Fleet. They still haven't sorted out the institutional contradiction between the military and Ubuntu philosophy. They want to be thoughtful, apologetic killers."

5357, "(fr)We don't waste time on apologies here, I can guarantee you that. The cliches about hotblooded Martians are true. This is our world and we're not giving it up to a league of upstart colonials."

5358, "(fr)I'm angry at the Tevs. I think they're arrogant and misguided, and I resent their claims to the moral high ground in an unprovoked, unilateral conflict. I want to punish their crimes."

5359, "(fr)I've got my own list of grievances against them...but I can't guarantee you we'll ever be able to deliver, pilot. This war is not a personal feud."

5360, "(fr)Sir, if you don't waste time on apologies, why are you so clearly wrapped up in guilt over the deaths of your pilots? If you'll pardon the presumption, sir."

5361, "(fr)You've got a lot of fucking nerve, Laporte. I read all about your discipline issues, and apparently they weren't exaggerated."

5362, "(fr)I heard all those cliches, sir, but the squadron seems strangely subdued for one of Two Fleet's infamous fighter kennels. I'm guessing the casualty rate has taken its toll."

5363, "(fr)It's pretty ballsy of you to bring it right up like that, Laporte...but you're both perceptive and correct. The chemistry died with most of the old pilots."

5364, "(fr)You're sharper than I expected. You don't have to beat around the bush. Give me your thoughts on my command performance, Laporte, you've clearly got some."

5365, "(fr)Sir, I left First Fleet to escape pervasive combat shock. But your attitudes towards these new pilots is giving me deja vu."

5366, "(fr)Sir, after some thought, I'm not comfortable with the breach of protocol this conversation implies."

5367, "(fr)Don't be timid about the issue. Give it to me straight."

5368, "(fr)My views on the problem are immaterial. It should be handled by command review through an appropriate authority. "

5369, "(fr)That's an easy attitude for you to take, Sublieutenant. Maybe you don't understand what it's been like out here these past few weeks. This is not the Solaris, safest ship in the fleet. We are right on the bloody edge here."

5370, "(fr)You're right, sir, I haven't been here. I can only speak to my current observations."

5371, "(fr)Sir, if you want to do something about that 400% casualty rate, stop treating the rookies like they're already dead. Make it clear that they're your people now."

5372, "(fr)Think very carefully about your next words, Sublieutenant, because you are in serious danger of coming up on charges. I do not have time or patience for this kind of idiocy."

5373, "(fr)Look, I'll be straight with you. I saw my last squadron bleed to death. Yours is worse - it's already dead. You don't have a squadron, sir, you have a factory for lost pilots."

5374, "(fr)I apologize, sir. I'll submit myself to review as soon as we return to the Indus. I'm accustomed to loose command discipline."

5375, "(fr)You're just determined to piss me off, aren't you, Laporte? You've put your foot in it, so follow through. Do you think I'm unfit to command this squadron?"

5376, "(fr)The fact that you're even asking me that question suggests you need to take some time to sort yourself out, sir. If you can't lead, then step aside."

5377, "(fr) I think that 400% casualty rate cut you so deep that you just gave up. You're afraid of what will happen if you let yourself get close again."

5378, "(fr)Who the hell do you think you are? I mean, listen to yourself, you smug, high-handed, condescending -"

5379, "(fr)Look, Simms, if you want to keep acting like these rooks are already dead, then that's going to turn into a self-fulfilling prophecy. Your call."

5380, "(fr)You know what, maybe you should be asking yourself that question. Who the hell are YOU to treat your rookies this way? What kind of commander does that make you?"

5381, "(fr)Don't even pretend to understand what's happened on this ship, Laporte. While you were salvaging waylaid freighters we were turning the butcher's bill into a goddamn chapter book out here."

5382, "(fr)Wake up, Simms! You know what happened to the Navajas! You're not the only soldier in the universe who's seen her squadron die a hundred little deaths!"

5383, "(fr)You are guilty of negligence, Simms, and the cold fact is that negligence is causing the deaths of your pilots. You don't want to care about them dying, so you let them die!"

5384, "(fr)All right, pilot, let's wrap this sortie up. Get a feel for the ship, and let me know if you have any special requests."

5385, "(fr)Sir, I have serious concerns about morale aboard the Indus. The other rookies believe you're holding them at arm's length because you expect them all to die."

5386, "(fr)Copy that, One."

5387, "(fr)Laporte, in case it somehow wasn't clear, this is a military unit, and you will behave like a flight officer. You are not in charge of rookie morale."

5388, "(fr)Copy that, sir. Buttoning up."

5389, "(fr)This is urgent, sir. If you don't seriously reconsider your attitude towards the new pilots, you're going to push the Indus's casualty rate up towards five hundred percent."

5390, "(fr)You know what? You're really pissing me off, Laporte. You act like discipline is just a set of guidelines. You lecture me about command attitude. Did your uncle treat you like some kind of princess? Is that the problem?"

5391, "(fr)Look, sir, if I were in your position, I don't think I'd act any differently. Your friends and comrades are dead. You're fundamentally alone out here. And you can't let yourself get close for fear of losing us too."

5392, "(fr)You know what pisses me off, sir? Waste. You've lost so many pilots that the only way you think you can survive is by detaching yourself. Well, we can all tell you're resigned to our deaths. And that kills people."

5393, "(fr)Oh, for fuck's sake, Sublieutenant. Go on. Tell me how you REALLY feel."

5394, "(fr)You have to do better, or these rooks will all die! You may have convinced yourself that there's nothing you can do, but that's simple dereliction of duty!"

5395, "(fr)What I've seen and heard this sortie has been a major disappointment, pilot. Your jacket and your previous conduct led me to expect better."

5396, "(fr)Sir! I'll try to comport myself more in line with your expectations."

5397, "(fr)You know what, sir, I could say the same about you. I came here to serve under an officer who could use my skills...not one hamstrung by self-pity."

5398, "(fr)Is this a joke? Do you think you can get away with that kind of insubordination?"

5399, "(fr)Any good command is built on trust, sir, and I don't trust you. None of the rooks do. You're too wrapped up in your own dead."

5400, "(fr)Get mad, Simms. Go volcanic. Anything's better than this detachment you've maintained."

5401, "(fr)You're a farce, Laporte. You're a testament to everything wrong with First Fleet. Military discipline is not some kind of optional accessory."

5402, "(fr)Military discipline exists to keep a unit functioning! And this unit, sir, does not function! This is a factory for cannon fodder!"

5403, "(fr)You know what's a farce, Simms? Your squadron. You are a satire of a commander, a paper tiger with all the leadership qualities of a voodoo omen. "

5404, "(fr)You are WAY out of line, Sublieutenant. This is your last chance to back down, or you're going to get real familiar with the brig."

5405, "(fr)I'm just trying to tell you what's wrong, sir. Because as things stand, this isn't a squadron that deserves my service."

5406, "(fr)Fine. So be it. What I'm saying has to be said, even if ends my career. Because your attitude towards these rookies is getting them killed."

